**RR-07 — Licensing comparable deal terms** (`research/r00-licensing-deal-terms.md`)
- A running royalty as a percent of sales dominates licensing (~62–72% of deals); an upfront is a minority add-on (~22%). LiT's upfront-plus-royalty pairing is conventional in form.
- The divergence is the **base, not the rate**: 1% NSR on *total* production value borrows streaming form while process-tech convention prices off *incremental* value created. That is the negotiation fault line a sophisticated major will press.
- Jetti is the closest analog and validates the asset-light licensor model directionally, but its per-deal terms are undisclosed — flagged `NEEDS EXTERNAL RETRIEVAL`, so "1% on total value is market" remains Unsupported.

**RR-08 — Adoption timeline at majors** (`research/r00-adoption-timeline.md`)
- Mining is a documented late, "race to be second" adopter; the burden of proof sits on the vendor.
- Jetti (better-positioned, producer-backed) took ~5 years founded-to-first-commercial and ~8 to a premium valuation. LiT's Month 25 first-license from a *pre-validation* start is an optimistic-tail outlier, not a base case.
- The Month 25 timeline and the no-bridge self-funding claim are the same optimistic assumption viewed twice; a slip in either breaks both — the central financing risk.

